On Jul 16, 2006, at 2:47 PM, Todd Super Bassist wrote:

>  I'd like to bounce this off you guys just to make sure I  
> understand this
> correctly. There is a REVERSE switch attached to the transmission  
> with TWO
> wires coming off of it.

Correct.

> What I'd like to know is, is this reverse switch basically just a  
> regular old
> switch? Does that switch complete the circuit between the two wires  
> that come
> off of it?

Yes. The resistance is infinite or zero. The switch doesn't ground  
either wire to the transmission case.

> If that's the case, then that would mean that ONE of those wires  
> would need to
> connect to a positive source while the other would connect to the  
> "Y" that
> goes to the back-up tail-lights.
>
> Am I correct in understanding this?
>
> If I understand that correctly, then would the positive on the COIL  
> be an
> acceptable positive source for the back-up wire?

That's how the factory did it and is reflected in the wiring diagrams.

> Oh! One other question, I noticed there is a second switch on the
> transmission. I had been told that this switch is OPEN when the car  
> is in 4th
> gear. What would be the purpose of that switch? Nothing seems to be  
> connected
> to it, and I don't see anything about it in the Bentley manual?

See page 73 of Engine & Clutch in Bentley. It's an electrically  
operated vacuum advance cutoff.

